The system with:
•	2 servers + 1 common queue
has better efficiency than 
•	2 servers + 2 separate queues 
even if both servers have the same service rate.
Why?
With 1 common queue:
•	customers go to the next available server automatically 
•	no server stays idle while another queue becomes long 
•	workload is balanced 
•	waiting time is reduced 
With 2 separate queues:
•	one queue may become overloaded 
•	one server may sit idle while customers wait in the other queue 
•	imbalance reduces overall efficiency 
1 Server + Multiple Queues
Example:
•	1 barber 
•	3 separate lines 
Problems:
•	One queue may become very long while another stays empty. 
•	Customers choose queues inefficiently. 
•	Server utilization may become uneven. 
•	More waiting time overall. 
Result:
•	Efficiency decreases 
•	Waiting time increases 
•	Queue management becomes poor 
________________________________________
Multiple Servers + 1 Queue
Example:
•	3 billing counters 
•	1 common queue 
Advantages:
•	Next free server takes the next customer immediately. 
•	Balanced workload among servers. 
•	Less waiting time. 
•	Better utilization. 
Result:
•	Efficiency increases 
•	Queue moves faster 
•	Better resource utilization
Steady State Behavior of Infinite Population Model
Definition
In an infinite population model, the number of customers/source population is assumed to be extremely large or unlimited. Customer arrivals are independent of the number already in the system.
The system reaches a steady state when:
•	arrival rate and service rate become stable over time 
•	queue measures stop changing significantly
2. Markovian Models
Definition
A Markovian model is a queueing model where:
•	arrivals follow Poisson distribution 
•	service times follow exponential distribution 
•	future state depends only on present state 
This is called the memoryless property.
3. Steady State Behavior of Finite Population Model
Definition
In a finite population model, the number of customers is limited. The arrival rate depends on how many customers are already in the system.
The system reaches steady state when probabilities of different states become constant over time.
